<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is the difference between HEX, RGB, and HSL color formats?", answer: "HEX uses a six-digit hexadecimal notation (#RRGGBB) where each pair represents red, green, and blue intensity from 00 to FF. RGB specifies color as three decimal values (0-255) for red, green, and blue channels. HSL describes color using Hue (0-360 degrees on the color wheel), Saturation (0-100% intensity), and Lightness (0-100% brightness). All three formats can represent the same colors but HSL is often more intuitive for humans." },
  { question: "What are WCAG contrast requirements?", answer: "The Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG) define minimum contrast ratios between text and background colors. Level AA requires 4.5:1 for normal text and 3:1 for large text (18pt or 14pt bold). Level AAA requires 7:1 for normal text and 4.5:1 for large text. These ratios ensure text remains readable for people with visual impairments, including those with color blindness or low vision." },
  { question: "How is color contrast ratio calculated?", answer: "Contrast ratio is calculated using the relative luminance of two colors. First, each sRGB color value is linearized. Then relative luminance is computed as L = 0.2126R + 0.7152G + 0.0722B. The contrast ratio is (L1 + 0.05) / (L2 + 0.05), where L1 is the lighter color. The ratio ranges from 1:1 (no contrast) to 21:1 (black on white)." },
  { question: "What is the HSL color model?", answer: "HSL represents colors using three components: Hue is the color type measured in degrees on the color wheel (0/360 is red, 120 is green, 240 is blue). Saturation is the color intensity from 0% (gray) to 100% (vivid). Lightness ranges from 0% (black) through 50% (pure color) to 100% (white). HSL is more intuitive than RGB because you can easily create variations by adjusting saturation or lightness while keeping the hue constant." },
  { question: "What are web-safe colors?", answer: "Web-safe colors are a set of 216 colors that display consistently across all monitors and browsers. They use only the hex values 00, 33, 66, 99, CC, and FF for each RGB channel. Web-safe colors were important in the 1990s when monitors were limited to 256 colors, but modern displays support millions of colors, making this limitation obsolete. Today, designers use the full 16.7 million color gamut without compatibility concerns." }
]) %>

